<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Response to the Ministry of Justice Consultation on</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">y The Equality And Diversity Forum (J</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">RR</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 0007)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Equality and Diversity Forum (EDF) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is a network of national organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">committed to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">equal opportunities, social justice, good community relations, respect for human rights and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an end to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">discrimination based on age, disability, gender and gender identity, race, religion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or belief, and sexual orientation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Further information about our work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is available at </span><a href="http://www.edf.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">www.edf.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and a list of our members is attached.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Equality and Diversity Forum (EDF) considers that Judicial Review is a vital remedy and one of the most important ways for citizens to hold Gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rnment and other public bodies to account.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an essential tool for the protection of human rights in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We note that the Ministry of Justice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">J)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in its foreword to this consultation has said that Judicial Review (JR) is ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a crucial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">check to ensure lawful public administration’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  This is a widely held view, Lord Dyson, now Master of the Rolls said – ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">there is no principle more basic to our system of law than the maintenance of rule of law itself and the constitutional protection affor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ded by judicial review’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The power to judicially review public decisions is an important reserve power enabling citizens to ensure good governance and further constraints on its use should be approached with very considerable caution.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Members of the EDF a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re extremely concerned that these proposed changes will have a seriously chilling and adverse effect on the availability of JR and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are concerned that, if implemented, they may adversely affect the ability of people in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to secure their human rights.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he reason given in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">J’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consultation Paper for seeking to limit access to Judicial Review is the fact that ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the use of judicial review has expanded massively’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The chart showing the number of judicial review applications for permission on page 8 (char</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t 1) shows a significant increase between 2007 and 2012 of immigration and asylum cases but the increase in all other civil cases has gone from about 2,000 in 2007 to 2,700 in 2012 we would query whether this is aptly described as a ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">massive expansion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’ jus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tifying the erosion of rights for non-asylum/immigration civil cases proposed in this consultation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Standing </span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are strongly concerned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that a narrower test for “standing” to apply for judicial review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will limit the ability of people to challenge the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">executive and thus to ensure human rights are protected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he current test that requires an applicant to show that they have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ‘sufficient interest’ in the matter in question </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> correct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any charity bringing legal proceedings must be able to show that they ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve an interest in the matter sufficient to ensure that they are acting within their charitable objects and not acting ultra vires</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> so t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">suggestion that such charities and NGOs commonly have little or no interest in the matter is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">misplaced: i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f they h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ad no interest in the matter then as a charity they would have no power to act as to do so would go beyond their charitable objects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We also note that recent research published by the Public Law Project has identified that between July 2010 and February 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">12 the vast majority of cases (77%) were brought by individuals and only 3% of the JR cases brought were brought by interest groups and charities.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The role of JR is to correct public law wrongs. This is of vital constitutional importance.  All members o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f society have an interest in the proper administration of executive power and it is for this reason that access to judicial review should be not restricted to those most directly affected by the matter at hand: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Public law is not at base about rights, eve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">n though abuses of power may and often do invade private rights; it is about wrongs – that is to say misuses of public power; and the courts have always been alive to the fact that a person or organisation with no particular stake in the issue or the outco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">me may, without in any sense being a mere meddler, wish and be well placed to call the attention of the court to an apparent misuse of public power. If an arguable case of such misuse can be made out on an application for [permission to bring judicial revi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ew], the court’s only concern is to ensure that it is not being done for an ill motive.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While it is not inconsistent with Article 6 ECHR for a State to have procedural rules relating to judicial review there comes a point when procedural rules become so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">restrictive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">curtail substantive rights to a remedy for wrongs.  We believe that the proposals to amend the rules on standing come very close to this line and may cross it in some cases.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Third party interventions </span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.86pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The role of interveners is to assist the Court. They are only permitted to intervene with the permission of the Court when the Court considers that they have something to add to the legal argument and the intervention will lead to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">better justice. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In many c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ases interveners have raised the human rights aspects of cases that may not have been raised by the parties themselves. We are there</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> concerned at the possibility of third party interventions in JR cases being prevented.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Costs – legal aid</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the proposed changes to legal aid are implemented then any directly affected person dependent on legal aid would find it very difficult to find a solicitor willing to start proceedings for him/her. This makes it more likely that JR will only accessible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to individuals with significant assets. Combined with the proposed restrictions on standing, the legal aid changes significantly increase the risk that Article 6 rights may be infringed.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The require</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ments of Article 6 ECHR include a substantive right of a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ccess to a Court.  This is very important as it imposes a positive obligation to provide legal aid in some cases.  Changing these procedural and legal aid rules would therefore be inconsistent with such positive obligations if they make the door to the Cou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rt too narrow.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">agree with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the President of the Supreme Court, Lord Neuberger in his Tom Sargent Memorial Lecture when he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> observed – </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘If a person with a potential claim cannot get legal aid, there are two possible consequences. The first is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">that the claim is dropped: that is a rank denial of justice and a blot on the rule of law. The second is that the claim is pursued, in which case it will be pursued inefficiently, and will take up much more of the court staffs’ time and of the judge’s time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> in and out of court. So that it means greater costs for the court system and in delay for other litigants’.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This proposal to limit legal aid so that providers are only paid for work carried out on judicial review cases where permission is granted, or ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ceptionally in the Legal Aid Agency’s discretion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would create a situation where individuals will find it very difficult to bring cases challenging the decisions of local authorities or central government because they will not be able to find lawyers willi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng to take the risk of not getting paid for this work. This will have the result that lawyers will stop doing this type of work and people facing injustice because of public law failings by public bodies will find it increasingly difficult to find anyone t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o advise them.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is neither reasonable nor sensible to expect individuals to take judicial review action without legal advice.  Litigants acting without advice are more likely to take cases that will not succeed, whatever their intrinsic merits, because </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the case has not been adequately prepared.  They are also more likely to take weak cases which might have been deterred by good legal advice at the outset.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Access to legal aid should not be available on a discretionary basis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">after</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a case is taken.  It is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not reasonable to expect solicitors to undertake cases in the hope of being paid.  The Government would not expect other small businesses/SMEs to undertake such a gamble. Subsidising litigation in this way will not be financially viable for firms that und</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ertake predominantly legal aid work.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – protective costs orders</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Protective Costs Orders (PCO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) have been developed by the Courts in order to ensure that there is an equality of arms between the claimant/s and the defendant. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As such, we believe they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">play a valuable role in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the set of mechanisms by which Article 6 rights can be secured. We do not see evidence of a case for changing the current arrangements.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Public Sector Equality Duty</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When implemented effectively, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Public Sector Equality Duty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (PSED)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can make an important contribution to the promotion and protection of human rights in areas such as education, health, social care, planning and policing where human rights are engaged on a daily basis.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It also helps to secure effective protection of Arti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cle 14 rights. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The government’s policy intention is that the primary pressure on English public bodies to implement the PSED should come via civil society and citizen engagement rather than through legal remedies</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. A regime of data publication and transparency has been put in place to help support this approach, although it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">too early to assess the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">success of these mechanisms.  In addition, the Equality and Human Rights Commission has some PSED enforcement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">powers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Despite the high media profile of some cases, enforcement via JR has played a small role in implementation of the PSED. Nonetheless</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, it is the only means by which individuals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can challenge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">whether </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">public bodies’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have met the PSED standards. As suc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h, JR has an important role to play in this particular area of human rights protection and promotion. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The EDF has considered </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">whether there are satisfactory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">alternatives to JR as a remedy for breaches of the PSED and we have not been able to think of any t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hat would be appropriate and not lead to even further delays in the process of decision making.  We do not think that an administrative or non-judicial process would be appropriate or effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Furthermore a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ny tribunal system would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">likely to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">subjec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t to greater delays than are experienced by the High Court and would not have powers equivalent to those exercisable by the High Court.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">question the arguments suggesting that an alternative is necessary. The Ministry of Justice’s consultation docum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent at page 30 observes that – </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 69.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘The review [the Public Sector Equality Duty Review] also found that, even where a court has ruled that a public body has failed to comply with the PSED, often it only orders that body to re-take the decision. It is not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">uncommon for the body to arrive at the same conclusion following further work to demonstrate it had discharged the duty effectively.’</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We surveyed all the cases of Judicial Review where the Public Sector Equality Duty in sectio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n 149 of the Equality Act 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> wa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s considered</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">summarised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> successful ones </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in our response to the MoJ’s consultation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  In six of these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cases</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the High Court granted an application for JR and in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">only one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of these cases did the public authorities concerned reach the same decision after further consideration of their equality duties.  One instance out of six cannot reasonably be called ‘not uncommon’ and we therefore conclude that the analysis in the consul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tation paper is flawed and does not provide a good basis for eroding the remedies available to the beneficiaries of the Public Sector Equality Duty.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">26</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Annex</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Equality and Diversity Forum members </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Action on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Hearing Loss</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Age </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">British Humanist Association</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">British Institute of Human Rights</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="fon