sources/357/Neuberger-2013-lecture.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.justice.org.uk/data/files/resources/357/Neuberger-2013-lecture.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The Scottish and Welsh governments have taken rather</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> different approaches to implementation of the PSED.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> We have not considered the case of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Stuart Bracking and others (Appellants) v Secretary of State for Work &amp; Pensions (Respondent)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> &amp;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Equality and Human Rights Commission (Intervener) Court of Appeal (Civ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">il Division), judgment 6 November 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as it is too early to assess the result.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>